Other likely interview questions & good answers

Q: How do you ensure consistency between MySQL and Kafka offsets?
A: Use a two-phase approach — write data and outbox row in same DB transaction, and have a reliable connector or Kafka transaction to publish. Or use an atomic offset store (consumer commits offset in checkpoint table after successful DB write). For perfect atomicity consider Kafka transactions or transactional outbox pattern.

Q: How do you handle processor crashes mid-state?
A: Use state persisted per state (checkpointing state machine progress in DB), versioning and idempotent operations. When worker restarts, it reverts to last committed state and replays remaining operations or resumes.

Q: What if the blob storage becomes a bottleneck for PDF writes?
A: Use parallel writes to blob, chunked uploads, and CDN for downloads. Also generate manifest + multiple blobs for very large invoices.

Q: How to handle schema evolution for line items?
A: Use schema registry, Avro/Protobuf with backward/forward compatibility, validate at producer, versioned processors.

Q: How do you test and QA such a system?
A: Unit tests for processors, integration tests against local Kafka/MySQL, chaos tests (killer scripts that kill workers), load tests with synthetic large invoices, and end-to-end regression tests including Spark jobs.

Q: What security measures are needed?
A: Encrypt PII in transit and at rest, RBAC for processing services, TLS for Kafka, signed blobs, audit logs.

Q: What monitoring / SLOs?
A: Track Kafka lag, number of pending workitems, processing time per invoice, PDF generation time, CPU/memory for processors, Spark job durations. Set alerts for consumer lag > X or average invoice latency > SLA.

Q: How to handle partial failures when generating PDFs?
A: Keep intermediate artifacts and retry with backoff; push failures to a DLQ; support manual replay and incremental pdf generation.

Q: Cost considerations for Spark or blob staging?
A: Use ephemeral clusters (Databricks/Azure Synapse) that spin up for large jobs; store compressed parquet for cheaper storage.

Summary & recommended design choices for your resume/interview

Checkpoint locking: implement atomic UPDATE ... WHERE status='PENDING' + lockedBy + lockExpiry (show SQL) — mention lease renewal and reclamation.

Priority: add priority column, ordered selection or dedicated high-priority worker pool and preemption mechanism.

Large invoices: route to Spark pipeline — blob staging, partition into chunks, distributed aggregation, merge, and finalize; avoid putting millions of messages into a single Kafka partition.

Kafka scaling: add partitions, use batching, autoscale consumers, and prefer blob pointer messages for extremely large payloads.

Partitioning: default key=invoiceId for ordering; for scale use invoiceId:shard with aggregator or blob staging to avoid hotspots.

Reliability: idempotent DB writes (ON DUPLICATE KEY), outbox pattern, job checkpoints, DLQ for failed events.

Operational: metrics (lag, queue depth), alerts, chaos testing.

